---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import KolamDivider from '../components/KolamDivider.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="Product Manager at GitHub, building support tools with craft and customer obsession.">
  <section class="page-container py-16 sm:py-24">
    <!-- Header -->
    <div class="max-w-2xl mb-16 reveal">
      <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold text-umber-800 dark:text-cream-100 leading-tight mb-6">
        About me
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-umber-600 dark:text-cream-400 leading-relaxed">
        I'm a Product Manager at <strong class="text-umber-800 dark:text-cream-200">GitHub</strong>, 
        working on Customer Success Engineering — the team that builds the internal tools 
        and systems powering GitHub's support experience.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-2xl">
      <h2>What I do</h2>
      <p>
        I lead product for support tooling — the forms customers fill out, the AI that helps 
        classify and route tickets, the dashboards agents use to resolve issues, and the 
        automation that handles what humans shouldn't have to. My work sits at the intersection 
        of <strong>customer experience</strong>, <strong>AI/automation</strong>, and 
        <strong>internal tools design</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        I believe support tooling is one of the best training grounds for product craft: real 
        users with real problems, measurable impact within days, enormous design challenges, 
        and the AI disruption wave hitting directly. Every feature I ship either saves a 
        customer time waiting, or saves an agent time searching — ideally both.
      </p>

      <KolamDivider />

      <h2>How I think about product</h2>
      <p>
        My operating philosophy comes down to a few principles I return to constantly:
      </p>

      <h3>🎧 Sit in silence with two customers</h3>
      <p>
        I have two customers — the end-users who encounter problems, and the support agents 
        who resolve them. Deep listening beats any pitch. "What grinds your gears?" is a 
        better question than "What feature do you want?"
      </p>

      <h3>📊 Leak the dashboard</h3>
      <p>
        Every metric I track should pass the "leak test": if accidentally shared with users 
        or agents, they'd be <em>ecstatic</em> about what's being measured. If a metric 
        wouldn't make your customer smile, it's measuring the wrong thing.
      </p>

      <h3>🎨 Tilt your umbrella</h3>
      <p>
        Taste is a competitive advantage. I optimize for reducing <em>thinking</em> (comprehension) 
        over reducing clicks. The goal is software that feels obvious — where the design 
        disappears and only the utility remains.
      </p>

      <h3>🚀 Ship, measure, celebrate, learn</h3>
      <p>
        Within two weeks of every feature ship, communicate the impact. Not because it's 
        "good optics" — because closing the feedback loop is how you build organizational 
        trust in product-led development.
      </p>

      <KolamDivider />

      <h2>Beyond work</h2>
      <p>
        I'm originally from India. I care deeply about craft in all its forms — whether 
        that's product design, typography, cooking, or the way a well-structured argument 
        unfolds. I believe the best work happens when you bring your full self to it, 
        not just your professional persona.
      </p>
      <p>
        I read widely (see my <a href="/reading">reading list</a>), think about design 
        systems more than most people, and am always looking for the next thing to build 
        with intention.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
